he Mexican Revolution, migrants traversed new layers of bureaucracy and authority amid shifting political regimes as they crossed and were crossed by borders. Ottoman Sephardi migrants in Mexico resisted unequivocal classification as either Ottoman expatriates or Mexicans through their links to the Sephardi diaspora in formerly Ottoman lands, France, Cuba, and the United States. By making use of commercial and familial networks, these Sephardi migrants maintained a geographic and social mobility that challenged the physical borders of the state and the conceptual boundaries of the nation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aCitizenshipzMexicoxHistoryy20th century. 0aEmigration and immigration lawzMexicoxHistoryy20th century. 0aJewszMexicoxHistoryy20th century. 0aJews, TurkishzMexicoxHistoryy20th century. 0aSephardimzMexicoxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh  aCitizenship.  aDiaspora.  aMexico.  aMigration.  aNetworks.  aOttoman Empire.  aPassports.  aSephardi.  aTransnational.  aTurkey.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2020 Englishz978311070477808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2020z9783110704570oZDB-23-DGF08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Frontlist eBook-Package 2020z978311069218140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150361322540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503613225423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503613225.jpg  a978-3-11-069218-1  SUP Frontlist eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070